The LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor is a project that involves using an Arduino board to read temperature from a temperature sensor and display it on an LCD screen. The system also uses a potentiometer to control the brightness of the LCD panel.

To set up the system, the temperature sensor, such as the DS18B20 or LM35, is connected to the Arduino board. The analog output pin of the temperature sensor is connected to the analog input pin of the Arduino board [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)]. The LCD screen is also connected to the Arduino board, with the second pin of the LCD connected to pin 3 of the Arduino board [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

To control the brightness of the LCD panel, a 10 K Ohm potentiometer is used. The first pin of the potentiometer is connected to the +VCC pin of the Arduino board, and the second pin is connected to pin 3 of the LCD [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

To program the Arduino board, the LiquidCrystal I2C library is used. This library can be installed through the Arduino IDE by searching for "LiquidCrystal I2C" in the library manager [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)]. The code for the project can be found online, and it involves reading the temperature from the temperature sensor and displaying it on the LCD screen [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd)].

JavaScript's built-in `sort()` method can be used to sort arrays. However, by default, it sorts strings in a case-sensitive manner. To achieve case-insensitive sorting, we can use the `localeCompare()` method or provide a custom comparison function to the `sort()` method.

## Step 3: Use the localeCompare() method
The `localeCompare()` method compares two strings and returns a value indicating their order. We can use this method to create a custom comparison function for the `sort()` method.

## Step 4: Create a custom comparison function
The custom comparison function should take two strings as arguments and return a value indicating their order. We can use the `localeCompare()` method to compare the strings in a case-insensitive manner.

## Step 5: Implement the solution

const arr = ["Hello", "world", "abc", "XYZ", "def", "ghi"];

This involves several steps, including registering your application in Azure AD, configuring Airflow's `airflow.cfg` file, and possibly setting up a custom authentication backend if needed.

Below is a simplified guide to help you generate the necessary configuration code for supporting Azure Active Directory SSO tokens in Apache Airflow. Note that specific details, such as client IDs and tenant IDs, will need to be replaced with your actual Azure AD application settings.

### Step 1: Register Your Application in Azure AD

Before configuring Airflow, you need to register your application in Azure Active Directory:

1. Go to the Azure portal (<https://portal.azure.com/>).
2. Navigate to Azure Active Directory.
3. Register a new application.
4. Configure the Redirect URI to point to your Airflow instance (e.g., `http://localhost:8080/login`).
5. Note down the Client ID and Tenant ID.
